Question 1: When would you want to use a remote repository rathrer than keeping all your work local?

Answer: In case you local becomes lost, stolen, corrupted it's good to have a remote for backups.

Question 2: Why might you want to always pull changes manually rather than having Git automatically stay up-to-date with your remote?

Answer: If more than one person is working on the code, a bug might be introduced, malicious intent might destroy the remote. 

Question 3: Describe the differences between forks, clones, and branches.  When would you use one instead of another?
  
  Forking and cloning both copy an entire repo to a new location. The difference is that forking is specific to Github and cloning
  is available to all of git. Branching is like a pointer to a linked list of your commits.
  
  When to use: Branching is used to add changes but keep a master version unchanged. Clone to work or backup some branch some repo to another 
  directory and fork is when you ant to make changes that are public on github.

Question 4: What is the benefit of having a copy of the last known state of the remote stored locally?

  The benefit is being able to have all the current changes stored locally so that you may test the software or add and remove anything as
  necessary.
  
